WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.360
Hi, my name is Benji Braun, and I'm really excited to talk to you today about getting

00:00:09.360 --> 00:00:14.980
data science in your customers' hands quickly and on a budget using RStudio Connect.

00:00:14.980 --> 00:00:19.219
This is an unconventional use of this product, which is really geared towards internal apps

00:00:19.219 --> 00:00:20.219
and resources.

00:00:20.219 --> 00:00:25.100
But I want to show you how you can use this product for customer-facing applications as

00:00:25.100 --> 00:00:26.620
well as internal ones.

00:00:27.020 --> 00:00:31.340
But before I get into that, I want to set the scene for how we started using RStudio

00:00:31.340 --> 00:00:35.020
Connect to publish customer-facing data science applications.

00:00:39.139 --> 00:00:41.459
It was back in the summer of 2020.

00:00:41.459 --> 00:00:44.500
We all remember, but many would like to forget that time.

00:00:44.500 --> 00:00:49.540
In addition to being in the middle of a lockdown and without childcare, my family and I had

00:00:49.540 --> 00:00:52.619
moved in with my in-laws to get some extra support.

00:00:52.619 --> 00:00:57.939
Moreover, my wife had gone full-time on her own new business back in January 2020, while

00:00:57.939 --> 00:01:02.860
I had joined a startup as the first technical employee in February 2020.

00:01:02.860 --> 00:01:06.059
Needless to say, it was a stressful time.

00:01:06.059 --> 00:01:09.860
I have a feeling this is a picture many of you with kids have, or at least can relate

00:01:09.860 --> 00:01:10.860
to.

00:01:10.860 --> 00:01:15.540
If you don't have kids, just imagine everything you were doing back in summer 2020, but add

00:01:15.540 --> 00:01:18.300
a two-year-old and a four-year-old to the mix.

00:01:18.300 --> 00:01:24.059
As all this was going on, my company, 202 Group, was dealing with a problem.

00:01:24.059 --> 00:01:26.779
We had built a good, streamlined data pipeline.

00:01:26.779 --> 00:01:30.940
We had sourced the necessary data we needed to make actionable insights for our customers

00:01:30.940 --> 00:01:34.099
and built the methods to ingest and store that data.

00:01:34.099 --> 00:01:38.339
We had effective ways to analyze and model the data and customize visualizations for

00:01:38.339 --> 00:01:39.339
end customers.

00:01:39.339 --> 00:01:44.500
We were using open data and data science to expose risk in critical national security

00:01:44.500 --> 00:01:49.620
supply chains, and our customers were clamoring for more so they could take action.

00:01:49.620 --> 00:01:55.059
But despite this tested process, we had a problem.

00:01:55.059 --> 00:01:59.019
We had a really poor UI UX, if you could even call it that.

00:01:59.019 --> 00:02:04.980
We were delivering everything in PDFs, PowerPoint, and Excel CSV files.

00:02:04.980 --> 00:02:07.339
This is a big problem for two reasons.

00:02:07.339 --> 00:02:12.720
The first is that once PowerPoints or PDFs or spreadsheets left our inbox, it was immediately

00:02:12.720 --> 00:02:13.940
out of date.

00:02:13.940 --> 00:02:18.500
The customer could still get value out of it, but they relied on us emailing them updates,

00:02:18.500 --> 00:02:20.619
which were out of date almost immediately.

00:02:20.619 --> 00:02:24.380
They needed an on-demand, up-to-date data.

00:02:24.380 --> 00:02:30.300
The second problem was that it wasn't an appealing way for the customer to consume the analysis.

00:02:30.300 --> 00:02:33.779
At first, you might not think that's such a big problem, but if your customer doesn't

00:02:33.779 --> 00:02:37.820
like the way they interact with your product, they won't use it.

00:02:37.820 --> 00:02:42.059
So if you actually want your analysis to be anything more than a science project, you

00:02:42.179 --> 00:02:45.539
need to make sure your customer likes the way they interact with it.

00:02:45.539 --> 00:02:50.339
And for us, as a small bootstrap startup, our customer liking the product meant still

00:02:50.339 --> 00:02:54.899
being in business by the end of the year.

00:02:54.899 --> 00:02:59.660
The customer needed to be able to explore on their own in a user-friendly way and get

00:02:59.660 --> 00:03:02.660
the data into formats that they were comfortable with.

00:03:02.660 --> 00:03:09.759
It needed to be dynamic to fix the stale data problem and the static interface problem.

00:03:09.759 --> 00:03:11.860
But we had other requirements as well.

00:03:11.860 --> 00:03:15.940
We needed to get this out the door quickly in the next few weeks, not months, and we

00:03:15.940 --> 00:03:18.539
didn't have very much money to do it.

00:03:18.539 --> 00:03:23.940
Last, but certainly not least, we needed something where we could continue to focus on the data

00:03:23.940 --> 00:03:26.059
science portion of our company.

00:03:26.059 --> 00:03:30.940
The thing that was differentiating us, the value we were actually delivering to customers,

00:03:30.940 --> 00:03:34.820
was the data science finding, not the interface itself.

00:03:34.820 --> 00:03:40.800
Learning web development technologies like CSS, HTML, JavaScript, PHP, would not only

00:03:40.800 --> 00:03:45.759
be a distraction, it would actively detract from our time developing the data science,

00:03:45.759 --> 00:03:50.600
which is where we were really driving value.

00:03:50.600 --> 00:03:55.440
So based on all this, we developed a set of five criteria we would use to evaluate the

00:03:55.440 --> 00:04:00.639
proposed solutions to this problem of getting up-to-date data science products in our customers'

00:04:00.639 --> 00:04:01.639
hands.

00:04:01.639 --> 00:04:04.080
It had to be cheap, like a few thousand dollars tops.

00:04:04.080 --> 00:04:06.240
It had to be easy to use.

00:04:06.240 --> 00:04:10.199
We needed to be able to focus on the data science and not spend a lot of time figuring

00:04:10.199 --> 00:04:12.080
out web technologies.

00:04:12.080 --> 00:04:13.960
It had to be easy to customize.

00:04:13.960 --> 00:04:18.720
Our customers were still figuring out what they wanted, and we needed to be able to adapt

00:04:18.720 --> 00:04:21.000
and make changes quickly and easily.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:23.320
The user had to log into an interface.

00:04:23.320 --> 00:04:27.760
The customer needed to be able to access up-to-date info when they needed it.

00:04:27.760 --> 00:04:30.279
Emailing stack reports had to add.

00:04:30.279 --> 00:04:32.880
And last, we had to retain our IP.

00:04:32.880 --> 00:04:36.440
Getting locked in with a vendor didn't seem like a good idea, and we wanted to maintain

00:04:36.440 --> 00:04:42.760
flexibility in the future if we started doing something new.

00:04:42.760 --> 00:04:44.940
So we settled on three options.

00:04:44.940 --> 00:04:51.359
We considered third-party BI tools like Tableau or Power BI, hiring a front-end developer,

00:04:51.359 --> 00:04:55.760
and last, RStudio Connect.

00:04:55.760 --> 00:04:58.040
Some of my teammates were pushing for this option.

00:04:58.040 --> 00:05:00.040
I was against it for a few reasons.

00:05:00.040 --> 00:05:04.760
The startup costs are actually pretty expensive, which is a big driver for us at this point.

00:05:04.760 --> 00:05:07.959
But there are two other, perhaps more important reasons.

00:05:07.959 --> 00:05:12.760
One is that learning to use one of these tools was really a poor use of our time.

00:05:12.760 --> 00:05:15.339
We already knew how to use R Markdown and Shiny.

00:05:15.339 --> 00:05:19.440
Why learn how to use one of these tools when we could be developing data science?

00:05:19.440 --> 00:05:23.040
If we were going to use these tools and learn how to use them from scratch, we might as

00:05:23.040 --> 00:05:25.200
well learn JavaScript ourselves.

00:05:25.200 --> 00:05:29.079
These tools might market themselves as easy to use, but in practice, I don't think it's

00:05:29.079 --> 00:05:34.239
really that easy, especially if you want to produce something appealing.

00:05:34.720 --> 00:05:39.119
The other thing is that we'd get locked into the vendor, and switching costs would be high.

00:05:39.119 --> 00:05:44.119
Anything we developed would be specific to the vendor's product, and we'd lose flexibility

00:05:44.119 --> 00:05:47.320
if we wanted to do something else.

00:05:47.320 --> 00:05:49.920
So third-party BI tools had two out of three.

00:05:49.920 --> 00:05:53.119
I was ready to move on.

00:05:53.119 --> 00:05:55.040
What about hiring for this need?

00:05:55.040 --> 00:05:58.519
The problem here was that it wasn't going to be cheap to get someone good, and while

00:05:58.519 --> 00:06:02.640
it might be easier than doing it ourselves, it would be hard to source someone good and

00:06:03.640 --> 00:06:08.119
We also wanted to stay focused on our value, which was in the data science, and hiring

00:06:08.119 --> 00:06:11.200
outside of that would also have been a distraction.

00:06:11.200 --> 00:06:17.880
If we were going to hire, we'd want to hire another data scientist or engineer.

00:06:17.880 --> 00:06:22.760
So better than the third-party tools, but still only three out of five.

00:06:22.760 --> 00:06:26.160
So this left us with RStudio Connect.

00:06:26.160 --> 00:06:30.279
I was only familiar with this product because I had goofed around enough in the RStudio

00:06:30.279 --> 00:06:35.559
IDE and clicked on this button here, the publish button.

00:06:35.559 --> 00:06:38.600
This was really helpful when I published a blog using RPUBs.

00:06:38.600 --> 00:06:44.040
So the idea of a button in the RStudio IDE to publish R Markdown and share them securely

00:06:44.040 --> 00:06:45.040
was really appealing.

00:06:45.040 --> 00:06:51.839
Then when I got in touch with RStudio about using Connect, I found out about the small

00:06:51.839 --> 00:06:53.239
business discount.

00:06:53.239 --> 00:06:57.399
This made this option far and away cheaper than the other options we considered.

00:06:57.399 --> 00:07:01.519
And since we got to keep using R Markdown, we didn't have vendor lock-in, and we retained

00:07:01.519 --> 00:07:03.899
all our own IP.

00:07:03.899 --> 00:07:07.480
So checks across the board.

00:07:07.480 --> 00:07:10.480
It checked all the boxes, which is why we used it going in.

00:07:10.480 --> 00:07:15.040
But the reason why we continued to use it, and I'm such an evangelist for it now, is

00:07:15.040 --> 00:07:17.399
what made it so simple.

00:07:17.399 --> 00:07:21.179
We were able to change, update, and push content quickly.

00:07:21.179 --> 00:07:26.160
We could respond to customers both in terms of access and data within minutes.

00:07:26.160 --> 00:07:30.720
And as time went on, we were iteratively able to learn more web and front-end technologies

00:07:30.720 --> 00:07:32.959
and incorporate them into the end product.

00:07:32.959 --> 00:07:38.079
This included custom CSS and JavaScript to give our products a unique look and feel and

00:07:38.079 --> 00:07:43.320
better user experience with only minimal front-end needs.

00:07:43.320 --> 00:07:47.359
So we've gotten to the point based on customer needs and where we are as a company that we

00:07:47.359 --> 00:07:54.079
now do deliver our product in a custom JavaScript PHP front-end with a dedicated front-end team.

00:07:54.079 --> 00:07:58.640
And now we use the RStudio Connect for its more conventional purpose of hosting internal

00:07:58.640 --> 00:07:59.640
products.

00:07:59.640 --> 00:08:02.880
But what's awesome is that everything we developed was in R Markdown.

00:08:02.880 --> 00:08:10.040
So those rendered HTML docs and graphics could be used by our front-end developers.

00:08:10.040 --> 00:08:13.440
So I want you to think about RStory and how it might work for you.

00:08:13.440 --> 00:08:17.880
If you're a small business or even individual, and you're not sure how to get your data science

00:08:17.880 --> 00:08:21.079
into your customers' hands, think of RStudio Connect.

00:08:21.079 --> 00:08:26.760
It's cheap, easy to use, easy to update your products, lets your customers log into an

00:08:26.760 --> 00:08:34.640
interface, and lets you retain all your IP without vendor lock-in.

00:08:34.640 --> 00:08:37.919
Please feel free to reach out to talk about this or anything else.

00:08:37.919 --> 00:08:40.159
Thank you so much for your time and coming to hear my talk.

